WEBVTT

00:11.330 --> 00:16.575
Welcome to Baria Temple International Church's Podcast.

00:16.595 --> 00:23.101
I am your host Timothy, and we're here together on this beautiful day to hear from God.

00:24.382 --> 00:33.351
Today, we're fortunate to have our beloved pastor, Michael Gonzalez, with us who will be sharing God's word.

00:34.612 --> 00:40.658
So let's all prepare ourselves to receive what God has in store for us today.

00:42.018 --> 00:42.679
Let's begin.

00:43.981 --> 00:44.642
This morning.

00:45.063 --> 00:58.225
And so I want to open up today's message with a very familiar passage of Scripture that is going to be the foundation of our time together.

00:58.706 --> 01:03.634
It's found in Galatians chapter 3 and verse 28.

01:06.658 --> 01:16.713
It says this, it says there is no longer Jew or Gentile, slave or free, male or, and female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus.

01:18.957 --> 01:20.239
Now hold there for a moment.

01:22.843 --> 01:26.669
We can't talk about the needs of our community.

01:27.851 --> 01:35.282
We can't talk about the difficulties of offering hope and healing to our community

01:35.778 --> 01:38.622
without addressing one very specific issue.

01:41.706 --> 01:49.518
So today we're going to dive into a topic that is both sensitive but extremely vital.

01:51.440 --> 01:55.867
And that is healing the racial divides that are so prevalent in our world.

01:57.569 --> 02:00.914
I wanna begin by saying that I don't have all the answers.

02:02.274 --> 02:14.092
This is an issue that is far more complex, far more deep, far more challenging than anything that I can do while I'm up here.

02:14.653 --> 02:16.115
But what I do know is this.

02:16.175 --> 02:22.204
As your pastor, I know my experiences differ from many of yours.

02:24.808 --> 02:28.594
But that I am here to learn from you, to listen to your stories,

02:28.674 --> 02:35.706
to stand with you in seeking justice and healing as we seek to heal our community as a church.

02:36.207 --> 02:43.439
Because together we are called to demonstrate the love of Christ united as one family.

02:44.942 --> 02:48.268
We are Berea Temple, a church for all nations.

02:49.710 --> 02:54.418
Every race, every color, every creed, every nationality, every language group,

02:55.362 --> 02:58.047
This is a place for the body of Christ.

02:58.407 --> 03:03.937
As we continue building our identity statement this year, we are declaring that we are.

03:03.997 --> 03:07.122
Would you please go back to the we are and I'll take care of the slides from there.

03:09.887 --> 03:10.548
That we are.

03:11.830 --> 03:16.999
This was the foundation of what we're talking about for this entire year.

03:17.440 --> 03:18.802
We are.

03:19.618 --> 03:21.901
whatever it may be.

03:22.261 --> 03:24.684
And then we moved on and we are a-g.

03:24.704 --> 03:32.194
I know this is a review for all of us, but I want us to kind of get again this idea as we dive in together.

03:32.594 --> 03:41.045
We are an assemblies of God, Pentecostal, spirit-filled, Bible-believing church at the corner of Compton and Russell.

03:41.345 --> 03:48.114
We are the body of Christ here in South City to rise up and to call Christ

03:48.226 --> 03:49.728
out to the nations.

03:49.748 --> 03:50.068
Amen.

03:51.550 --> 03:54.893
We are part of the body that is here.

03:54.953 --> 03:56.255
We are church members.

03:56.635 --> 04:02.622
We are people who are called to offer hope and healing to our community.

04:05.265 --> 04:15.135
And we must recognize the role that we play in bringing healing to one of the most painful and unfortunately persistent issues in our city today.

04:16.397 --> 04:17.458
The racial divides.

04:19.138 --> 04:25.486
Our city is made up of numerous dozens of different nationalities.

04:27.008 --> 04:34.218
The largest is the Bosnians and then the Afghanis and the list goes on and on.

04:34.278 --> 04:44.431
If you're ever interested, I keep a list of all of the nations in my office and I pray over those regularly because this is who we are as a church.

04:44.831 --> 04:46.994
This is who we are called to be.

04:47.330 --> 04:52.378
So today I've titled my message just that, healing racial divides.

04:53.580 --> 04:56.184
Within our congregation, we are a family.

04:56.224 --> 05:12.850
We are united by our faith in Jesus Christ, yet outside these four walls in the broader community of our city, our beloved city of St. Louis, there are issues of racial division that are very real and very, very deeply felt.

05:14.978 --> 05:21.227
These divides are not just abstract concepts, they're not things that are at fingertip length.

05:22.349 --> 05:29.199
They are very real and very deeply painful and they impact many right here in our own city and beyond.

05:31.622 --> 05:34.386
And I know that many of you have been directly affected

05:34.498 --> 05:38.484
by racial tensions and injustices that have happened within our community.

05:38.764 --> 05:52.104
And while I may not have been here during certain pivotal moments within the city of St. Louis, I can understand how those have impacted the lives of those people that call our great city home.

05:52.385 --> 05:57.973
And they continue to shape our shared experiences as we live in St. Louis.

05:59.175 --> 06:03.762
As a church, we must be committed to standing against the sin

06:04.802 --> 06:11.309
of division and prejudice, which has caused deep wounds even within the Christian community.

06:13.150 --> 06:19.277
So today, as we address this topic, there's a lot of places that our eyes and our minds could go.

06:21.018 --> 06:32.690
But I want us to focus in on how we, as the body of Christ, the body of Christ that stands tall and proud with a loud voice at the corner of Compton and Russell.

06:33.794 --> 06:41.883
how we can be, we've talked a lot this over the last two years about being a beacon of hope to our city.

06:42.844 --> 06:49.071
That is what the church has called to, how we can be a beacon of hope and healing to those around us.

06:50.792 --> 06:52.354
So that is our focus today.

06:52.674 --> 07:03.346
So the first thing, again, if you're a notetaker, the first way that we can be a beacon of hope and healing on this specific issue is by recognizing our unity

07:03.522 --> 07:04.123
in Christ.

07:05.665 --> 07:12.356
Ephesians chapter 2 and verse 14, it reminds us that for Christ Himself has brought peace to us.

07:12.716 --> 07:22.732
He united Jews and Gentiles into one people when in His own body on the cross He broke down the wall of hostility that separated us.

07:24.394 --> 07:29.362
This passage shows us that Jesus is the one who breaks down the walls that divide us.

07:30.242 --> 07:33.206
uniting us into one body through his peace.

07:33.667 --> 07:35.829
He is the one who breaks down the walls.

07:36.210 --> 07:48.667
He is the one, is the only place that we are going to find the walls, the connection, the continuity, the unity of putting back together is only gonna be found in Jesus.

07:48.727 --> 07:55.956
We spoke last time we were together that no government plan, policy, or program is gonna be able to fix these issues.

07:56.037 --> 08:00.082
It is only the voice and the hand of the Almighty God.

08:04.002 --> 08:10.013
Many people in our community are struggling with division, with barriers that separate them from one another.

08:10.754 --> 08:15.964
But here inside the body of Christ, we know that these barriers have already been torn down.

08:16.244 --> 08:18.248
Jesus Himself is our peace.

08:18.529 --> 08:21.554
And through Him, we are united in one.

08:21.762 --> 08:36.045
Consider more recent moments in our own city where communities have come together to stand against racial injustice and to advocate for change, whether this is marches or walks, festivals or community awareness events.

08:36.386 --> 08:46.281
In these times, people of all backgrounds joined hands and raised their voices, breaking down the barriers and pushing for more a more just society.

08:47.764 --> 08:49.106
Just like those efforts,

08:49.442 --> 08:52.467
for justice and reconciliation in our own community.

08:53.288 --> 09:03.004
We too, the church, we must actively work to tear down the invisible walls that divide us, race, culture, social.

09:04.466 --> 09:17.106
These have to be broken down within the body of Christ, where we come together as a single voice, unified, crying out in the wilderness, returned to Jesus, know the Father,

09:19.810 --> 09:27.281
Our church, I believe wholeheartedly, must be a living testimony to this truth.

09:29.064 --> 09:30.005
So here's a question.

09:31.688 --> 09:40.501
As we reflect on the unity that we have in Christ, I want us to take a moment and examine our own individual hearts.

09:42.825 --> 09:45.609
Are there any biases or prejudices that we've held on to?

09:48.273 --> 09:48.914
Perhaps

09:49.666 --> 09:55.992
Even unconsciously, things that we've just allowed to creep into our lives.

10:00.256 --> 10:09.685
Are there any of those that we need to bring before the Lord for healing in our own hearts so that we can be hope and healing to our community?

10:10.085 --> 10:14.349
We can be a catalyst for healing in the city of St. Louis.

10:15.771 --> 10:19.154
Because we talk about revival has to start in me, right?

10:20.642 --> 10:22.424
Salvation has to start in me.

10:23.285 --> 10:25.087
Peace has to start in me, right?

10:25.127 --> 10:27.550
Well, then so does this.

10:29.052 --> 10:31.194
So does dealing with our own issues.

10:32.796 --> 10:33.837
That has to start in me.

10:33.877 --> 10:35.279
It has to start in my heart.

10:38.883 --> 10:48.114
As we interact with our neighbors, our friends, our coworkers, or even those that we worship with, we should reflect the unity that we have in Christ.

10:48.802 --> 10:55.451
By doing so, we can offer the world a glimpse of what true community looks like.

10:57.073 --> 11:01.980
When people look at Berea Temple, I tell people this all the time.

11:03.482 --> 11:09.790
We worship with traditional, regular, what we would call English-American worship songs.

11:10.271 --> 11:18.802
We worship in Spanish, we've worshiped in French, we've worshiped in Swahili, we've worshiped in Kana, we've worshiped in Ibo,

11:19.970 --> 11:24.617
We've worshiped in multiple languages, multiple styles of worship.

11:25.619 --> 11:33.031
We have people from eight different nations represented within the body of Christ at Berea Temple.

11:34.113 --> 11:39.121
I tell people, if you wanna see what heaven's gonna look like, come to Berea Temple on a Sunday morning.

11:40.303 --> 11:47.314
If you wanna hear what worship is gonna sound like, come to Berea Temple and worship with us in one of our worship services.

11:49.922 --> 11:59.195
We have the opportunity to give the world a glimpse of what community is supposed to look like.

12:00.196 --> 12:06.825
Maria Temple can be a community where love overcomes division, peace triumphs over hostility.

12:09.208 --> 12:09.949
I want to stop here.

12:12.533 --> 12:19.282
I want us to take a moment to think about how we can demonstrate this unity both individually

12:20.130 --> 12:21.973
and collectively as a church body.

12:22.895 --> 12:24.558
It's great to talk about it.

12:24.798 --> 12:33.192
It's great to talk about the ethereal, the concepts, the ideas, but it doesn't matter if we don't put boots on the ground.

12:33.413 --> 12:37.039
We've talked about that all through this series of hope and healing.

12:38.281 --> 12:43.410
What can we do both individually and collectively as a church body

12:44.162 --> 12:46.527
to demonstrate this kind of unity.

12:46.827 --> 12:55.525
Individually, we can reach out to someone different than us, have meaningful conversations and stand against prejudice wherever we encounter it.

12:55.845 --> 13:04.362
But we must also recognize that true healing requires us to address the systemic issues of inequality and racism.

13:05.565 --> 13:06.226
It has to.

13:07.522 --> 13:19.195
As a church, we can actively support local justice initiatives, we can partner with organizations working towards equality, and we can advocate for change in our community.

13:20.336 --> 13:31.929
Together, we can make a tangible difference, living out our faith, not just in words, but in actions that promote justice and reconciliation for everybody.

13:34.072 --> 13:36.274
Because we are all the church.

13:37.698 --> 13:41.943
I am, if you haven't picked up yet, I am big on we are the church.

13:43.164 --> 13:45.367
We are the body of Christ.

13:47.109 --> 13:49.451
We together stand.

13:50.452 --> 13:56.299
We together, I don't care what color, race, socioeconomic status.

13:56.659 --> 14:02.706
I don't care if you have more money than Donald Trump or if you're as broke as, well, we won't reference you.

14:06.594 --> 14:09.797
When we step in here, you are my brother and sister.

14:10.378 --> 14:13.581
And if you need me to lift you up, I'm gonna lift you up.

14:13.641 --> 14:15.282
If you need a hug, we're gonna hug.

14:15.603 --> 14:20.567
If you need to sit down and counsel, I don't care what the schedule says, we will sit down and we will talk.

14:21.649 --> 14:29.736
Inside here, we are the body of Christ, and we are brothers and sisters under one King, under one daddy.

14:31.198 --> 14:32.279
This is who we are.

14:32.699 --> 14:35.602
We are the church.

14:37.154 --> 14:38.535
Second, if you're a notetaker.

14:38.856 --> 14:45.562
The second way we can offer hope and healing to our community on this issue is by acknowledging the pain and struggles.

14:45.602 --> 14:49.026
It does us no good to try to avoid it.

14:49.086 --> 14:54.131
It does us no good to try to hide or ignore it or to claim that it doesn't exist.

14:54.191 --> 15:02.159
Romans chapter 12 and verse 15 says, it encourages us to be happy with those who are happy and to weep with those who weep.

15:02.179 --> 15:05.202
Another translation says to rejoice with those

15:05.538 --> 15:09.544
who rejoice and to mourn with those who mourn.

15:10.305 --> 15:18.016
It doesn't say that we're the recipient of the mourning issue, but that we come along and we mourn with them.

15:18.057 --> 15:24.466
And so if you are mourning, we as your brothers and sisters

15:24.770 --> 15:25.531
more than with you.

15:25.872 --> 15:39.711
There are too many stories in our world's history, stories of wars and atrocities, all in the name of religion, race, or retaliation against a people group who are different than another people group.

15:39.731 --> 15:52.690
From the division of food found in the book of Acts, to the Spanish Inquisition, to the slavery across the globe, to the Holocaust, and to far too many individual stories found in our own current events.

15:55.234 --> 16:02.464
You think of the pain that these stories carry, the fear, the loss, the sense of injustice.

16:04.466 --> 16:08.852
Even if these experiences aren't our own, they're very real to our brothers and sisters.

16:09.973 --> 16:11.616
I'll tell you a story that I have.

16:13.899 --> 16:16.562
We were offered tickets this last week to go

16:16.642 --> 16:26.420
They very often give pastors these free tickets to go see these Christian movies that come out and they want to get feedback on what pastors think.

16:26.681 --> 16:31.590
Mostly, they want us to go watch it for free so that we'll tell you to go buy a ticket and go watch that movie.

16:31.931 --> 16:33.293
But, you know, that's what it is.

16:34.315 --> 16:35.497
We know what it is, it's okay.

16:36.539 --> 16:40.146
But I was offered free tickets and we went and we saw the movie.

16:40.226 --> 16:43.590
And as we got into it, I realized the type of movie that it was.

16:43.931 --> 16:51.080
And I leaned over to Sister Leticia and I said, if I would have realized that it was one of these movies, I would never have accepted the tickets.

16:51.321 --> 16:57.308
It was a movie about the Holocaust and about the atrocities that happened during that time.

16:58.370 --> 17:07.602
My heart has a hard time processing because my brain immediately goes to the pain.

17:07.682 --> 17:18.873
Nobody can rightly put onto a screen the horror that our Jewish brothers and sisters had to deal with through that season.

17:20.635 --> 17:25.320
Not knowing day to day, moment to moment, if their life was over.

17:27.022 --> 17:35.250
And to try to put that into a picture, anything that they create is gonna be woefully short

17:39.074 --> 17:44.299
But regardless, as a church, we're called to mourn with those who mourn.

17:44.580 --> 17:46.702
And so we mourn with our brothers and sisters.

17:46.762 --> 17:56.312
Again, whether it's through any of these things that we listed, you know, obviously we weren't here through the Inquisition and most of us in this room at least are not here through World War II.

17:58.574 --> 18:05.842
But for our brothers and sisters are dealing with issues within our own current events, we stand in solidarity with them.

18:06.498 --> 18:10.564
and we mourn with those who mourn, and we listen to their stories with open hearts.

18:10.944 --> 18:22.200
Stories like this remind us of the struggles of others, even when possibly distant from our own, may be different than what we've experienced.

18:23.041 --> 18:28.970
But it doesn't mean that they're not anymore real, and we stand with them through whatever the situation is.

18:29.290 --> 18:32.114
In our city, there are many who are mourning

18:32.674 --> 18:36.779
mourning the pain and the injustice that racial divides have caused.

18:37.380 --> 18:42.606
As a church, we are already a community deeply committed to unity and healing.

18:43.427 --> 18:53.700
Yet we know that there's always more we can do to deepen our understanding and to extend our compassion to those who are hurting in the wider community.

18:56.223 --> 18:59.047
I think of the story of the Good Samaritan found in Luke chapter 10.

19:00.168 --> 19:01.650
This is a Jewish man

19:01.890 --> 19:03.633
who's beaten and left for dead.

19:03.913 --> 19:15.189
And it's not the religious leaders that pass by, but the Samaritan, someone from a group of people that is despised by the Jews, who stops and helps him.

19:15.450 --> 19:17.693
He bandages his wounds and he cares for him.

19:17.893 --> 19:29.490
He takes him to an inn and he even pulls money out of his own pocket and says, here, this should take care of him, but if there's not, if there's any more ode, I'll take care of it on my return.

19:32.002 --> 19:44.314
The Samaritan acknowledged the pain of someone who would typically be seen as an enemy, showing compassion and love that crossed societal boundaries, regardless of what that boundary was.

19:47.417 --> 19:59.890
We need to be like the good Samaritan, acknowledging the pain that others feel, even when it may seem distant from our own experience, even if we don't understand

20:01.794 --> 20:08.643
We acknowledge, we empathize, and we come and we stand in unity.

20:11.747 --> 20:23.463
By opening our hearts to the stories and the experiences of others, we fulfill our calling to mourn with those who mourn and to be instruments of healing in our city.

20:25.626 --> 20:31.314
Because again, we are a church who is called to offer hope and healing.

20:32.674 --> 20:34.155
Doesn't matter what the topic is.

20:34.836 --> 20:37.559
The topic is irrelevant.

20:37.579 --> 20:43.745
We are first responders to the spiritual needs of our community.

20:44.766 --> 20:48.029
Praise the Lord for paramedics and firefighters and police.

20:48.769 --> 20:53.234
They do a job that is in sometimes unimaginable.

20:55.456 --> 21:01.842
But we as the body of Christ, we run in when other people just go, whatever.

21:02.850 --> 21:03.951
leave them to their own device.

21:07.856 --> 21:12.080
I see so much listening and compassion already within our church.

21:15.084 --> 21:31.442
I want us to continue to build on this foundation by engaging even more in community events and initiatives that promote healing of all kinds, using the strength that we already have to foster reconciliation and support to those in need.

21:32.130 --> 21:43.748
I want us to find opportunities to participate in activities that foster reconciliation and healing across the barriers that the enemy wants to use to keep us apart.

21:45.330 --> 21:48.435
Did you catch who I mentioned?

21:50.599 --> 21:51.180
The enemy.

21:53.143 --> 21:55.346
He is the father of all wise.

21:55.938 --> 21:58.400
He is the father of division.

21:58.901 --> 22:07.589
He is the father of disunity, of discord, of chaos, not Christ.

22:10.912 --> 22:19.080
This is how we put our faith into action and bring tangible healing to our city.

22:20.302 --> 22:24.946
This is how we as the body of Christ can stand up

22:25.154 --> 22:29.059
and offer hope and healing to the City of St. Louis.

22:32.242 --> 22:40.813
The third way that we can offer hope and healing to our community is by pursuing reconciliation and healing.

22:40.853 --> 22:41.874
We have to acknowledge it.

22:43.476 --> 22:48.562
We have to acknowledge that it exists and then we have to pursue with a reckless abandon.

22:48.674 --> 22:50.817
reconciliation and healing.

22:50.877 --> 22:59.547
Second Corinthians chapter 5 and verse 18 says, and all of this is a gift from God who brought us back to Himself through Christ.

22:59.908 --> 23:05.354
And God has given us this task of reconciling people to Him.

23:05.615 --> 23:11.762
It doesn't say reconciling Jews, it doesn't say reconciling Gentiles, it does not make a specific

23:11.938 --> 23:17.630
address to a people group of socioeconomic status, a particular region or culture.

23:17.931 --> 23:22.340
It says to reconcile people to him.

23:22.360 --> 23:32.402
In our city, there is a desperate need for reconciliation, for bridges to be built where walls have once stood.

23:34.754 --> 23:44.186
as a church we're called to be ministers of reconciliation, not just within our own community, but beyond our walls, into the broader city.

23:45.608 --> 23:49.553
But reconciliation is not just about bringing people together.

23:49.593 --> 23:52.436
It involves seeking justice.

23:54.058 --> 24:03.570
Like many who have gone before us, we must be relentless in our pursuit of reconciliation, breaking down barriers and building bridges wherever we go.

24:04.258 --> 24:10.449
Micah chapter six and verse eight tells us that, no, oh people, the Lord has told you what is good.

24:11.009 --> 24:18.683
And this is what he requires of you to do what is right to love mercy and to walk humbly with your God.

24:18.923 --> 24:30.162
We are called not only to build bridges, but to pursue justice, to love mercy for our community and to teach them how to walk with our God.

24:30.786 --> 24:44.082
We are called to bring reconciliation, not only reconciliation in the racial issue, but in their own heart with the creator, the maker of heaven and earth.

24:46.786 --> 24:58.886
It is our responsibility to take the hope and healing that we experience here and extend it outwards to be ambassadors of Christ's reconciliation in our neighborhoods and our cities.

24:59.267 --> 25:01.991
We are ambassadors.

25:03.374 --> 25:13.170
We are the people who go out from God's house, from his home, and we take the message

25:13.314 --> 25:21.925
of hope and healing to our neighborhood, to our neighbors, to our jobs, to our schools, to our other community events.

25:22.245 --> 25:27.893
We are the ambassadors who speak the truth of Jesus to a lost and dying world.

25:29.374 --> 25:33.860
And I recognize that this journey towards reconciliation and unity isn't easy.

25:34.020 --> 25:34.701
I get that.

25:36.243 --> 25:41.650
There will be moments of discomfort, misunderstandings, and frankly, even setbacks.

25:42.690 --> 25:54.602
Yet we must remain committed, understanding that the path to healing often requires courage, perseverance, and a whole lot of God's grace.

25:57.265 --> 26:02.690
While the road may be challenging, we are strengthened by our faith in Jesus Christ.

26:05.273 --> 26:10.098
He has already overcome the world, and he calls us to be his peacemakers.

26:13.442 --> 26:17.206
He has already overcome the world.

26:20.330 --> 26:24.715
So when we move forward, we don't need to move forward in anger.

26:25.896 --> 26:28.098
We don't need to move forward in hostility.

26:28.779 --> 26:35.026
We don't need to move forward in fear because he's already overcome the world.

26:36.428 --> 26:38.450
So now we move forward

26:38.562 --> 26:43.009
already knowing the outcome and we become his ambassadors.

26:43.109 --> 26:49.919
We become his mouthpiece because he has already spoken how this ends.

26:50.139 --> 26:54.586
And so we simply can step into the role of peacemaker.

26:57.009 --> 27:03.058
So what are some specific ways again that we can engage in reconciliation efforts?

27:03.746 --> 27:09.091
We can partner with other local churches or organizations working toward community healing.

27:09.372 --> 27:15.438
We can host community forums where people can share their experiences and work together towards understanding.

27:15.718 --> 27:22.705
We can support initiatives that provide opportunities for cross-cultural interactions and learnings.

27:24.146 --> 27:29.091
These actions help break down barriers and build bridges of understanding and peace.

27:30.253 --> 27:31.634
But let's not stop there.

27:32.962 --> 27:40.786
Let's also think about how we can take these actions further, both individuals and as a church body.

27:41.122 --> 27:50.994
Individually, we can reach out to our neighbors who may have different backgrounds and engage again in meaningful conversations and stand against the prejudice wherever we encounter it.

27:51.215 --> 28:03.730
As a church, we can be proactive in forming alliances with community leaders, advocating for justice in local issues and developing programs that foster unity and reconciliation within our community.

28:05.058 --> 28:16.132
Together we can embody the message of Christ's love in every sphere of our influence, showing the world what true unity looks like.

28:17.494 --> 28:33.714
We as the body of Christ, we as Berea Temple, we as an international church, we can be the church that shows our community what real

28:34.722 --> 28:38.466
Christian fellowship and real Christian love looks like.

28:40.629 --> 28:53.503
As we continue to live out our identity as AG church members who offer hope and healing to our community, want us to remember and to celebrate the many ways that we've already been doing this.

28:55.665 --> 29:00.130
I see ways in which we as a church have already reached out to those in need.

29:00.430 --> 29:03.794
We had a food pantry program when I first got here.

29:04.130 --> 29:12.603
And unfortunately, by no fault of ours, the program had to close because our supplier no longer had the supplies to provide for us.

29:13.224 --> 29:19.795
But we were willing, we stood out and stood in the gap during a time that was necessary.

29:20.055 --> 29:24.402
We extended our love beyond our role, our walls.

29:25.346 --> 29:31.094
We hosted seek and say, and we gave away hundreds and hundreds of bags of groceries.

29:31.294 --> 29:33.617
We had conversations with homeless.

29:33.817 --> 29:35.840
We had conversations with our neighbors.

29:36.101 --> 29:39.165
We saw the community come together.

29:44.031 --> 29:49.398
The issue of division and pain that we see in our city is real.

29:51.161 --> 29:55.026
And God has positioned us and is equipping us.

29:55.426 --> 29:58.570
to continue to be part of the solution.

29:59.911 --> 30:08.902
So as we close today, want us to declare together the vision that God has given us as a church body.

30:14.769 --> 30:15.150
We are.

30:16.091 --> 30:16.612
Would you do this?

30:16.732 --> 30:17.553
Would you say with me?

30:17.633 --> 30:17.953
We are.

30:19.816 --> 30:20.637
We are AG.

30:22.379 --> 30:22.759
Thank you.

30:23.760 --> 30:25.202
We are AG church members.

30:28.290 --> 30:32.557
We are AG church members who offer hope and healing in our community.

30:37.366 --> 30:38.288
That is who we are.

30:41.353 --> 30:43.056
See, this isn't just a dream.

30:43.176 --> 30:46.161
It's a reality that we're working toward every day.

30:48.666 --> 30:51.090
Everything we do as a church

30:52.290 --> 30:56.896
should be focused around offering hope and healing to our community.

30:56.916 --> 31:03.964
Next year, as we move into our new theme, we're going to make a bit of a turn, not a hard turn, but a bit of a turn.

31:05.165 --> 31:09.991
It still is about offering hope and healing to a lost and dying world.

31:10.011 --> 31:15.698
It is still about being part of our community because this is more

31:16.578 --> 31:18.000
than just a saying.

31:18.360 --> 31:20.262
It's more than a one-time discussion.

31:20.582 --> 31:24.967
It is a commitment that we as a body of Christ are making.

31:29.352 --> 31:38.462
We need to choose to be peacemakers and bridge builders every day in our conversations, in our actions, and in our community engagements.

31:43.588 --> 31:45.810
We need to seek out ways to learn

31:46.242 --> 31:54.194
to grow and to stand together as a church, and that truly reflects the unity and diversity of God's kingdom.

31:55.976 --> 32:04.088
This is a journey that we are all on together, and it requires dedication, it requires prayer, and it requires action.

32:05.651 --> 32:15.986
As we move forward, I want us to commit to being a church that doesn't just talk about healing, but actively works toward it day by day,

32:16.066 --> 32:17.088
step by step.

32:18.051 --> 32:29.938
We will keep finding new ways to live out our calling, partnering with others, and continually seeking God's guidance on how we can be agents of His peace and His reconciliation.

32:32.386 --> 32:54.290
Revelation 7 and verse 9 says, In this passage we see a vision of the future.

32:54.402 --> 33:02.856
a great multitude that no one could count from every nation, tribe, people, and language standing before the throne and before the lamp.

33:02.876 --> 33:16.018
This is the vision of God's kingdom, and this is the vision that we hold at Berea Temple International Church, a church for all nations from every nation, every tribe, every people, and every language.

33:16.514 --> 33:19.118
Let this be our declaration.

33:19.359 --> 33:20.921
Let this be our mission.

33:21.162 --> 33:23.105
Let this be our identity.

33:23.305 --> 33:28.153
That Berea Temple International Church is a church for all nations.

33:29.856 --> 33:37.929
We are called to reflect the unity and diversity of God's kingdom bringing hope and healing to all.

33:41.475 --> 33:43.378
So as we reflect on today's message,

33:46.466 --> 33:53.735
Let's commit to taking those small but powerful steps towards being agents of peace and being agents of reconciliation.

33:53.775 --> 34:00.564
Let's ask God to help show us how we can contribute to healing the divides in our community.

34:02.766 --> 34:06.811
Before we close in prayer, I invite you to take a moment of silent reflection.

34:07.873 --> 34:15.442
Ask God to reveal any personal biases or areas where you can contribute to healing racial divides that plague our community.

34:16.834 --> 34:24.465
And let's commit to being peacemakers and healers and bridge builders in our city.

34:26.408 --> 34:35.462
Father, we ask you, we ask for your guidance as we seek to be peacemakers and healers and bridge builders in the city of St. Louis.

34:36.804 --> 34:46.418
Unite us in your love and help us to be a light that shines brightly in the darkness, reflecting the hope and healing that only you can bring.

34:46.658 --> 34:52.347
Empower us with boldness and courage to act on the message we've heard today.

34:53.629 --> 34:57.995
In the name of Jesus, we've prayed.

34:58.015 --> 35:00.639
In a moment as our worship team plays our final song.

35:02.983 --> 35:12.978
If you haven't yet experienced healing and unity that comes through knowing Jesus as your Lord and Savior, we want to give you that opportunity today.

35:14.850 --> 35:19.978
This decision could be your first step towards peace and reconciliation.

35:20.018 --> 35:25.847
Not only in your life, but in the lives of those around you.

35:25.867 --> 35:33.499
And if you're here today and you don't have peace in your heart, you're going pastor, I'd love to be a peacemaker.

35:33.539 --> 35:35.181
I'd love to be a bridge builder.

35:35.542 --> 35:41.731
I'd love to be part of the solution, but I am so caught up in my own heart.

35:42.312 --> 35:43.634
I don't have peace.

35:44.258 --> 35:49.507
you're invited to come and to find a place at the altar, and to simply pour your heart out to the Father.

35:49.808 --> 35:52.092
You don't have to pour it out to me, I'm not your priest.

35:53.615 --> 35:58.183
But you can pour it out to the Father, and He can heal your heart.

36:00.427 --> 36:04.434
So as we sing, you're invited to come, amen.

